Note that in this release, the PURLs for all NCIT xrefs changed, resulting in a large diff report.

 * Neuro
    * relaxed owldef of medial septal nucleus, as it was causing incorrect inferences. Fixes [1356](https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/issues/1356), [tgbugs](https://github.com/tgbugs)
    * Added placeholder definition for medial septal complex clarifying that it includes the diagonal band nucleus as well as MSN
 * Histology
    * Reviewed stroma/parenchyma design pattern
    * NT: parenchyma of mammary gland, fixes [1349](https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/issues/1349)
    * histology notes for bladder, see https://github.com/monarch-initiative/monarch-disease-ontology/issues/366
    * CP stroma: fixing def and adding cellular composition
    * relabeled/defining vagina stroma
 * Skeletal
    * NTRs for joints of auditory ossicles, https://github.com/obophenotype/mammalian-phenotype-ontology/issues/2305
    * Changed connected-to to connects for inter-limb regions, fixes [1355](https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/issues/1355)
    * tweaking def of TMJ, add notes to nasal fin
 * Meta
    * Use OBO purl for NCIT, fixes [1350](https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/issues/1350)

### Changes for: [temporomandibular joint](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0003700)

 * _Deleted_
    *  **-** [temporomandibular joint](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0003700) *[database cross reference](http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboInOwl#hasDbXref)* [C32888](http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C32888)
    *  **-** [temporomandibular joint](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0003700) *[definition](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000115)* A joint of the jaw that connects the mandible to a temporal bone. There are two TMJs, one on either side, working in unison. The unique feature of the TMJs is the articular disc. The disc is composed of fibrocartilagenous tissue (like the firm and flexible elastic cartilage of the ear) which is positioned between the two bones that form the joint. The TMJs are one of the only synovial joints in the human body with an articular disc, another being the sternoclavicular joint. The disc divides each joint into two. The lower joint compartment formed by the mandible and the articular disc is involved in rotational movement -- this is the initial movement of the jaw when the mouth opens. The upper joint compartment formed by the articular disk and the temporal bone is involved in translational movement -- this is the secondary gliding motion of the jaw as it is opened widely. The part of the mandible which mates to the under-surface of the disc is the condyle and the part of the temporal bone which mates to the upper surface of the disk is the glenoid (or mandibular) fossa[WP]. { [database cross reference](http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboInOwl#hasDbXref)=[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporomandibular_joint](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporomandibular_joint) } 
 * _Added_
    *  **+** [temporomandibular joint](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0003700) *[comment](http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment)* There are two TMJs, one on either side, working in unison. The unique feature of the TMJs is the articular disc. The disc is composed of fibrocartilagenous tissue (like the firm and flexible elastic cartilage of the ear) which is positioned between the two bones that form the joint. The TMJs are one of the only synovial joints in the human body with an articular disc, another being the sternoclavicular joint. The disc divides each joint into two. The lower joint compartment formed by the mandible and the articular disc is involved in rotational movement -- this is the initial movement of the jaw when the mouth opens. The upper joint compartment formed by the articular disk and the temporal bone is involved in translational movement -- this is the secondary gliding motion of the jaw as it is opened widely. The part of the mandible which mates to the under-surface of the disc is the condyle and the part of the temporal bone which mates to the upper surface of the disk is the glenoid (or mandibular) fossa[WP].
    *  **+** [temporomandibular joint](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0003700) *[database cross reference](http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboInOwl#hasDbXref)* NCIT:C32888
    *  **+** [temporomandibular joint](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0003700) *[definition](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000115)* A synovial joint of the jaw that connects the mandible to the temporal bone. { [database cross reference](http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboInOwl#hasDbXref)=[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporomandibular_joint](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporomandibular_joint) }
